---
import ChapterLayout from "../layouts/ChapterLayout.astro";
import BinderHoles from "../components/BinderHoles.astro";
import Backlink from "../components/Backlink.astro";
---

<ChapterLayout title="Case Studies" headVoice="publisher">
  <div data-voice="publisher">
    <BinderHoles />
    <Backlink />
    <p class="eyebrow">(Worked Examples of Play)</p>
    <blockquote>
      <p>
        The surest way to learn <a href="/table-of-contents">Severed Story</a>
        is to watch a workday unfold. What follows are a few worked examples — scenes
        narrated as they might happen at your table, with every Roll laid bare. Read
        them with
        <a href="/procedural-guidelines">Procedural Guidelines</a>
        close at hand.
      </p>
    </blockquote>
    <hr />
    <h2>Meet the Employee</h2>
    <p>
      Across these examples we follow <strong>Nina H.</strong>, a refiner in
      Macrodata Refinement. Her HRPE assessed her as
      <strong>The Analyst (DR)</strong>. The parts of her LIEP that matter here:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong>DREAD row:</strong>
          3 Temper Points, with
          <strong>WIT</strong>
          checked as a Core Competency, and 1 Kier Point.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong>FROLIC row:</strong>
          2 Temper Points.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong>Stress:</strong>
          beginning the day at
          <strong>Satisfactory</strong>.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
    <hr />
    <h2>Example One — A Routine Request</h2>
    <p>
      Nina&#x27;s Floor Manager asks her to fetch a file from a cabinet whose
      lock has jammed. The drawer is stubborn; the manager is watching.
    </p>
    <p>
      The GM decides the outcome is both <em>uncertain</em> (the lock is fighting
      her) and <em>meaningful</em> (her manager is judging her), so a
      <strong>Roll</strong>
      is called. The action — careful, quick problem-solving under a superior&#x27;s
      eye — is best embodied by
      <strong>WIT</strong>, whose parent Temper is
      <strong>DREAD</strong>. The GM sets the Task Severity at
      <strong>Demanding (15)</strong>.
    </p>
    <blockquote>
      <p><strong><u>Nina&#x27;s Roll</u></strong></p>
      <p>
        <strong>Principle:</strong>
        WIT (DREAD row) &nbsp;·&nbsp;
        <strong>Task Severity:</strong>
        Demanding (15)
      </p>
      <p>
        WIT is a <strong>Core Competency</strong>, so Nina rolls with
        <strong>Confidence</strong>. The action serves Lumon, so her
        <strong>Kier Point</strong>
        in the DREAD row applies.
      </p>
      <p>
        2d20 → <strong>9</strong>
        and
        <strong>16</strong> — take the 16.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>16 + 3 Temper + 1 Kier = 20.</strong>
        20 ≥ 15 →
        <strong>Success.</strong>
      </p>
    </blockquote>
    <p>
      The lock yields with a satisfying clunk. Nina hands the file over; her
      manager offers a rare, warm nod. A small, wholesome moment — the kind a
      quiet quarter is built from.
    </p>
    <hr />
    <h2>Example Two — A Bad Afternoon</h2>
    <p>
      Hours later, the day has worn on Nina. A string of interruptions has
      pushed her stress up to
      <strong>Poor</strong>. When a rattled coworker snaps at her over a shared
      terminal, she tries to calm them down.
    </p>
    <p>
      The GM rules this a <strong>CHEER</strong> action (parent Temper
      <strong>FROLIC</strong>) — not one of Nina&#x27;s Core Competencies. And
      because she is at
      <strong>Poor</strong>, the GM exercises the option to impose
      <strong>Hesitance</strong>
      on the Roll. Task Severity:
      <strong>Demanding (15)</strong>.
    </p>
    <blockquote>
      <p><strong><u>Nina&#x27;s Roll</u></strong></p>
      <p>
        <strong>Principle:</strong>
        CHEER (FROLIC row) &nbsp;·&nbsp;
        <strong>Task Severity:</strong>
        Demanding (15) &nbsp;·&nbsp;
        <strong>Hesitance</strong>
      </p>
      <p>
        2d20 → <strong>11</strong>
        and
        <strong>1</strong>
        — Hesitance takes the
        <strong>lower</strong>: the 1.
      </p>
      <p>
        A natural <strong>1</strong>
        is a
        <strong>Critical Failure</strong>, regardless of Modifiers.
        <strong>Nina&#x27;s stress rises by 1.</strong>
      </p>
    </blockquote>
    <p>
      Nina says exactly the wrong thing. The coworker recoils, wounded, and
      stalks off — and now there is bad blood between them. The GM rules this a
      <strong>Problem</strong>: Nina writes a &quot;P&quot; in her left-most
      stress box and notes the grudge under
      <strong>Stress Related Circumstances</strong>. Unlike ordinary stress, a
      Problem&#x27;s mark will not wipe clean with tomorrow&#x27;s descent — it
      must be <em>resolved through play</em> first.
    </p>
    <p>
      One natural 1 has turned a small slight into a thread the GM can pull for
      workdays to come. That is the engine of
      <a href="/table-of-contents">Severed Story</a>
      doing its work.
    </p>
    <div data-panel-type="note">
      <div>
        <svg
          xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
          width="24"
          height="24"
          viewBox="0 0 24 24"
          fill="none"
          stroke="currentColor"
          stroke-width="2"
          stroke-linecap="round"
          stroke-linejoin="round"
        >
          <path d="M15 2H6a2 2 0 0 0-2 2v16a2 2 0 0 0 2 2h12a2 2 0 0 0 2-2V7Z"
          ></path>
          <path d="M14 2v4a2 2 0 0 0 2 2h4"></path>
        </svg>
      </div>
      <div>
        <p><em><strong>The Other Path.</strong></em></p>
        <p>
          <em
            >The handbook ends Nina&#x27;s scene the moment she serves Lumon. Of
            course it does. But look at what it skips past: the drawer is open,
            and a name she knows is staring up at her.</em
          >
        </p>
        <p><em>She could take a page.</em></p>
        <p>
          <em
            >That is not the cabinet roll — that one is finished and won.
            Slipping a page up her sleeve under a manager&#x27;s eye is a
            separate act, and so it earns a separate, additional Roll: a new
            one, this time under
          </em><em><strong>WILES</strong></em><em>
            (the MALICE row), made in secret. No Core Competency to lean on this
            time, and no Kier Point to spend — because this act does not serve
            them. It serves
          </em><em><u>her</u></em><em>. So it is her </em><em
            ><strong>Ricken Points</strong></em
          ><em>
            that carry the Roll, and a success <strong>may</strong> earn her a Ricken
            Point into that row, if the GM feels that this moment of defiance calls
            for it. Should she fail it, the manager catches the motion of her hand
            — and that is a Problem all her own.</em
          >
        </p>
        <p>
          <em
            >One workday. One jammed drawer. But two separate Rolls living
            inside it — the one they asked her to make, and the one they would
            never know she made.</em
          >
        </p>
        <p><em><strong>— C.C.</strong></em></p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <hr />
    <hr />
    <p>
      That is play in <a href="/table-of-contents">Severed Story</a>. The rest
      is the story you and your players tell with it.
    </p>
    <p>Enjoy your time within these hallowed halls!</p>
  </div>
</ChapterLayout>
